\begin_layout Section*
Conclusions and future work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a given WDN, we presented ways to arrive at a sensor and actuator placement
 strategy.
 This sensor and actuator network design is useful for water authorities
 to detect contaminants and isolate the contaminated area in the event of
 an attack on the WDN.
 We proposed a multi-objective linear programming formulation that gives
 the optimal sensor and actuator cardinality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The formulation can reproduce the results of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "key-6"

\end_inset

 after relaxing the full requirements to partial, viz.
 to prevent further contamination of demand nodes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A performance benchmark of the simultaneous framework and the sequential
 non-linear optimization solution would be an illuminating exercise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This formulation introduces an 
\begin_inset Formula $O(NV)$
\end_inset

 blowup in the number of decision variables, but there exist techniques
 to solve such specifically constrained variables much faster.
 An implementation using such techniques would be useful for assessing real
 performance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integration of an implementation of these algorithms with existing open-source
 toolboxes for sensor and actuator placement is a possible future action,
 which makes the techniques presented here much more accessible.
\end_layout

